Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also discusses limited interaction, which is relevant to computer networks and communication systems, making cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) another likely sub-category. The paper also uses hypercontractivity and properties of the R\'enyi divergence, which are relevant to machine learning and data science, making cs.MM (Machine Learning) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) possible sub-categories. Finally, the paper proposes a new conjecture for binary symmetric sources, which is relevant to statistical inference and probability theory, making cs.SI (Statistics) a possible sub-category as well.
